{
  "text": "Our goal has been to provide a framework that can be used to critically assess whether phenomena are or are not maternal effects. Therefore, we have neither presented a comprehensive analysis of all possible phenomena (if that were even possible) nor a comprehensive review of all things labelled 'maternal effects'. We emphasize that the evolutionary and ecological consequences of maternal effects are distinct from those of the various other phenomena that we would not classify as maternal effects. We argue that an overly broad definition may encompass so many functionally distinct phenomena that it is not useful and, in fact, can obscure the unique evolutionary importance of maternal effects (e.g. [CITATION_1] . For example, models of trait evolution that incorporate maternal effects (e.g. [CITATION_2] ) will fail to predict or explain the evolutionary dynamics of traits that are influenced by cytoplasmic effects or genomic imprinting rather than true maternal effects.",
  "citation_candidates": [
